omeone was shooting at them, but, because a norwegian weather balloon showed up on radar, and scared the living shit out of a vodka-striken silo commander. It gets worse, even our leader's are freaked.<br><br>Tony Blair and Sam Nunn wrote..<br><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> The deterrent practices that were once necessary during the Cold War now constitute a dangerous anachronism, for three fundamental reasons. First, Russia's severe budget crunch has strained its nuclear posture to the point that Russian generals can no longer be confident of reliable retaliation after absorbing a systematic U.S. first strike. Second, russia is moving to a quick-draw nuclear posture at a time when its ability to decide rationally whether to pull the nuclear trigger is diminishing....Third, the budget crunch facing the Russian military threatens to undermine the entire Russian system of command and control over its nuclear arsenal.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br><br>Lets say Commander Vladamir gets a phone call that we're all gonna die, and to push the little red button. Before he can be stopped, because Ivan made a bad interpretation of a smudge on the radar screen, we're all blown into oblivian. Get the picture?<br><br>Oh, im not done.<br><br>The United State's continued reliance on Nuclear Proliferation as a policy initiative will only push other nations such as India to further nuclear development. <br><br>Koch, 98<br><br><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> As the chief of non-proliferation advocate, the UNited States has a significant interest in halting proliferation. Yet, perversely, the United States continues to pursue a hypocritical nuclear policy that encourages others to proliferate...What particularly peeked India's ire was the fact that the nuclear powers have not adequately fulfilled their obligation to move toward nuclear disarmament as promised under that Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT).  Policymakers in new Delhi wonder why Washington, Beijing and Moscow should be allowed to retain enormous nuclear arsenals when India, the world's largest democracy, is denied that right.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br><br>So, whats the solution?<br><br>Disarming all of our nuclear weapons.<br>Yes, we can keep the conventional ones little Timmy, and yes, you can go play at Brian's tonight. Why disarm dad? What about deterrence, wont we get the crap blown out of us? Dad? Dont make me give the nukes back! WAAAAAHHH!!!!<br><br>Well, I can rant about disarm being flawed later. First I'll give a little plan of action.<br><br>Disarm treaty. Ratified by all nations that have or are suspected of having nuclear weapons. IMF and UN perform inspections on all nations as designated in the treaty. Only nuclear weapons will be disarmed. All such facilities will be destroyed. Remember, the IMF and UN verifies all such destruction. Getting people to agree to such a treaty isnt a problem. Ive got cards to prove it, but im sleepy. So start bitching, debate mode = On. <p><a href = "http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=62888" target = "_blank">Drakz Soulsnacks</a><br>BlackRage Gravelord</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/udeaath1.showPublicProfile?language=EN>deaath1</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Journeyman</span><br> <font color=#ff0000>(7/9/02 6:44:06 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub42.ezboard.com/fayonaerofrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1656.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: In light of Blearchie's lack of flames..here goes.</span><hr size=1> Go ahead and disarm. We are gonna keep out nukes though. There not pointed at us so we are not afraid of them. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#383838><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub42.ezboard.com/uquantium61.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Quantium61</A></spa